; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:2) (Implem Version:1)
uses WFTypes, aWFRuleDesc
function MortalityTable(Age : Int4) return tWFNum8 uses aWFStandAloneRule
var tmpRule : aWFRuleDesc
tmpRule = self.GetExactRuleToExecuteFromRankInRuleDesc(0, self.CurrentDate) if tmpRule <> Nil aWFStandAloneRule(tmpRule.MyOwner).AppendParam(Age, 0, tmpRule) tmpRule.GetStandAloneResult(_Result, self) aWFStandAloneRule(tmpRule.MyOwner).CleanParamsAfterExecution(tmpRule) else self.AppendComment('No rule version defined at this date') endIf endFunc
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : tWFAmount) ; The annual premium is based on the mortality table and the chosen coverage amount Result = 2.5 * (100 - self.MortalityTable(self.Subscriber__Age__At_Subscription)) Result = 2 * Result * self.Option__CoverageAmount / 1000 endProc

aWFRuleDesc.RuleDescription: Dividends are like a premium given back
aWFRuleDesc.RuleText:
; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:2) (Implem Version:1)
uses aWLIOfferedInvestmentWithProfitSharingAndInterests
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : Num8) if (self.Dividend__Type = cpsPayOut) or (self.Dividend__Type = cpsReduceLoanAmount) or (self.Dividend__Type = cpsPayLoanInterest) if not self.Contract__IsMEC ; the cost basis is decreased and the gain is increased Result = -self.Dividend__Amount else if self.Option__Gain > 0 if self.Option__Gain < self.Dividend__Amount ; if dividends are greater than gain, taxes are paid on gain and the gains go into the cost basis Result = -self.Dividend__Amount + self.Option__Gain else ; if dividends are less than gain, taxes are paid on dividends and the dividends go into the cost basis Result = -self.Dividend__Amount + self.Dividend__Amount endIf else Result = -self.Dividend__Amount endIf endIf elseif self.Dividend__Type = cpsAccumulation if not self.Contract__IsMEC Result = 0 else if self.Option__Gain > 0 if self.Option__Gain < self.Dividend__Amount Result = self.Option__Gain else Result = self.Dividend__Amount endIf else Result = 0 endIf endIf elseif self.Dividend__Type = cpsPaidUpAddition Result = 0 elseif self.Dividend__Type = cpsPremiumReduction Result = -self.Dividend__Amount endIf endProc
aWFRuleDesc.Name: Cost Basis Impact

aWFRuleDesc.RuleText:
; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:2) (Implem Version:1)
uses WFTypes, aWLICoverageAmountAndPremiumVersion
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : tWFAmount) if self.Option__TerminationDate <= self.CurrentDate Result = 0 else if self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvInsidePUA Result = self.Option__PaidUpPremiumAmount * (self.Option__AgeInYears - self.Option__AgeInYearAtCoverageAmountEffectiveDate) else Result = self.Option__AnnualPremiumAmount * self.Option__AgeInYears * 0.9 endIf endIf endProc
aWFRuleDesc.Name: TCV

aWFRuleDesc.RuleText:
; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:2) (Implem Version:1)
uses WFTypes, aWLICoverageAmountAndPremiumVersion
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : tWFNum8) var Choice : tWFAmount var initialDate : tWFDate
if self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvInsidePUA Result = self.Option__CoverageAmount + self.Option__PaidUpPremiumAmount elseif (self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvSubscription) or (self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvEndorsement) Choice = 50000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) Choice = 100000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) Choice = 150000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) Choice = 200000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) elseif self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvReduction initialDate = self.Option__SubscriptionDate self.IncYears(8, initialDate) Result = self.Option__CoverageAmountAtDate(self.CurrentDate - 1) * (self.CurrentDate - self.Option__SubscriptionDate) / (initialDate - self.Option__SubscriptionDate) elseif self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvPaidUpConversion Result = self.Option__CoverageAmount endIf endProc

aWFRuleDesc.RuleDescription: Impact on cost basis: -Non MEC: the cost basis is reduced first, then the gain -MEC: the gain is reduced first and then the cost basis (withdrawing from the gain has no impact on the cost basis)
aWFRuleDesc.RuleText:
; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:1) (Implem Version:1)
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : Num8) if not self.Contract__IsMEC if self.DeliveredService__GrossSurrenderAmount <= self.Option__CostBasis Result = -self.DeliveredService__GrossSurrenderAmount else Result = -self.Option__CostBasis endIf else if self.DeliveredService__GrossSurrenderAmount > self.Option__Gain Result = -(self.DeliveredService__GrossSurrenderAmount - self.Option__Gain) else Result = 0 endIf endIf endProc
aWFRuleDesc.Name: Cost Basis Impact

aWLIOfferedIndividualLifeCoverageWithCas.Description: {\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033\deflangfe1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fswiss\fprq2\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}} {\colortbl ;\red153\green51\blue0;} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\nowidctlpar\lang2057\f0\fs16 Permanent life insurance coverage for as long as you live and continue to make timely premium payments.\par With level premiums and the accumulation of cash values, whole life insurance is a good choice for long-range goals. The guaranteed cash values can provide money later on to help with temporary needs or emergencies.\par \par \cf1\b\fs20 Features of Whole Life Insurance\par \cf0\b0\fs16\par Premiums generally are level and payable for life: Since premiums are level, the younger you are when you purchase a whole life policy, the less expensive the annual premiums will be.\par \par \b Dividends:\b0 Whole life insurance policies can earn dividends. Dividends result when our actual life insurance costs turn out to be less than we assumed in setting our premiums. Dividends are not guaranteed, since we don't know our actual costs in advance. \par \b Guaranteed Cash Values:\b0 Unlike term life insurance, which does not accumulate any cash values, some of the money you pay into your whole life policy accumulates as guaranteed cash values. If you choose to surrender the policy, these guaranteed cash values would be available to you. Or, as long as the policy is in force, you may borrow against them as a policy loan at the current policy loan interest rate. \par \par The amount of your guaranteed cash value depends on the kind of whole life policy you have, its size and how long you have had it. The growth in cash values is tax deferred under current federal income tax law. Borrowed amounts reduce the death benefit and cash surrender value. \par \par \par }
